_exec_summary.SummaryText:
A Risk Management Plan (RMP) was initially submitted on July 21, 1999 for Sunoco, Inc. (R&M)?s Sunoco Chemicals Neal Plant, hereafter referred to as the Neal Plant, located in Kenova, West Virginia.  The RMP program at the Neal Plant is in compliance with all requirements of Title 40 of the Code of Federal Regulations, Part 68 (40 CFR 68).  This document provides a brief overview of the following elements of the RMP:

* The accidental release prevention and emergency response policies at the stationary source;
* The stationary source and regulated substances handled;
* The general accidental release prevention program and chemical-specific prevention steps;
* The five-year accident history;
* The emergency response program; and
* The planned changes to improve safety.

ACCIDENTAL RELEASE PREVENTION AND EMERGENCY RESPONSE POLICIES:

Sunoco is committed to operating and maintaining all processes at the Neal Plant in a safe and responsible manner.  Sunoco continuously trains Neal Plant employees in facility operating procedures and performs ongoing preventative maintenance on process equipment.  The Neal Plant uses a combination of accidental release prevention programs and emergency response planning programs to manage the hazards associated with the regulated chemicals used on site.  By maintaining these programs, the Neal Plant ensures the safety of plant personnel as well the safety of the public and the protection of the environment.     

STATIONARY SOURCE AND REGULATED SUBSTANCES:

The Neal Plant is a polypropylene production facility.  The process regulated under the RMP is the Propane and Propylene Areas that include Propylene Railroad Tank Car Unloading, Propylene and Propane Storage, Propylene Purification, and Polypropylene Production.  The Neal Plant utilizes propylene along with catalysts, additives, and hydrogen in the production of polypropylene.  Propane is obtained from the propylene purification step.  Both propylene and propane are flammable chemica
